When considering limits at infinity of rational functions, only the
dominant term matters:

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \to -\infty} \frac{5x^3-2x^2+1}{6x^3+7} &= \lim_{x \to -\infty} \frac{x^3 \left( 5 - \frac{2}{x} + \frac{1}{x^3} \right)}{x^3 \left( 6 + \frac{7}{x^3} \right)} \\
&= \lim_{x \to -\infty} \frac{5 - \frac{2}{x} + \frac{1}{x^3}}{6 + \frac{7}{x^3}} \\
&= \frac{5}{6}
\end{align*}

Here we factored out the leading term (the $x^3$) on both the top and
bottom. That allowed us to cancel it and then evaluate the rest of the
limit. The $1/x^n$ terms go to zero as $x \to \infty$.
